<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_75.HTM>

Bluetongue in Spain in Balearic Islands
-------------------------------
(Date of previous outbreak of bluetongue in Spain reported to the
OIE: November 2000 [in Balearic Islands).
Translation of information received on 27 Oct 2003 from Dr
Arnaldo Cabello Navarro, Deputy Director General of Animal
Health, Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food, Madrid:
Report date: 27 Oct 2003.
Location of the outbreak: Sant Lluis district, Menorca island.
The total number of animals kept on the holding is 78 sheep.
Total No. of cases: 8 sheep.
Total No. of deaths: 7 sheep.
Total No. of animals destroyed: 1 sheep.
Diagnostic test used: PCR.
Source of agent / origin of infection: under investigation.
Control measures:
- stamping-out started;
- control of arthropods;
- control of wildlife reservoirs;
- quarantine of the premises;
- movement control inside the country;
- screening;
- zoning.
OIE Animal Health Information Department
<information.dept@oie.int>
Further details will be published in the next issue of Weekly Disease
Information, available online as from Fri 31 Oct 2003 afternoon
(GMT).
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The 2000 incident included over 1000 animal deaths and
vaccination of 319 000 sheep. Prior to this outbreak the disease
had not been seen in the Balearic Islands since 1960. Peter
Rodier's comments on the upsurge in the Mediterranean are worth
a look; see Bluetongue, upsurge - Mediterranean basin
20011122.2864. - Mod.PC]
